<P>
ADS DOMINATED BALLOT SPENDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than half of the $129 million spent on November, 1988, ballot measures was 
used to hire political consultants and purchase television and radio 
commercials, the state's political watchdog agency said. 
</P>
<P>
The Fair Political Practices Commission, reviewing $124 million in itemized 
expenditures of $500 or more, reported that 35% of the money -- $43.4 million 
-- purchased broadcast advertising. About 21% -- $26 million -- paid for 
political consulting services. Another 16% -- $20.2 million -- involved 
monetary or in-kind contributions to other political committees, primarily 
among the 15 committees battling over five insurance initiatives on the 1988 
ballot. The insurance battle over Propositions 100, 101, 103, 104 and 106 
consumed $91.3 million in itemized expenditures of $500 or more, the FPPC 
reported. 
</P>
