<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOME QUESTIONS FOR THE SERIOUS CYCLIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN WEYLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The novice cyclist can buy all the right equipment and wear all the right 
clothes, but it will take lots of time on the road to build endurance . . . not 
to mention, conversational savvy. 
</P>
<P>
Talking intelligently about cycling can be tough. 
</P>
<P>
And you certainly want to say the right things between pulls off the water 
bottle, right? 
</P>
<P>
Just so you'll know what concerns the serious cyclist, here's a sampling from a 
recent questionnaire in Bicycling magazine: 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the best food before a long ride? 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the best food after a long ride? 
</P>
<P>
 -- Where's the worse place on your body to get road rash? 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the best-tasting sports drink? 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the worst make of car that can pass you on a narrow road? 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the best way to get grease off your hands? 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the best cure for chain suck? 
</P>
<P>
This all may sound intimidating, but after you put in a few hundred miles, 
you'll have opinions -- and probably first-hand experiences -- to relate. JOHN 
WEYLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BICYCLES; BICYCLING; LIFESTYLES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
