<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ESPN and the NFL reached agreement on a new $450-million, four-year contract, 
similar to one agreed to last week by Turner Broadcasting, which will have 
cable rights to Sunday night games during the first half of the next four 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
ESPN will get 35 regular-season Sunday night games in the second half of the 
1990-93 seasons, eight next season and nine in each of the next three. 
</P>
<P>
ESPN will also televise three exhibitions and the Pro Bowl each year. 
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, ESPN became the NFL's first cable outlet, televising eight 
Sunday night games in the second half of each season. It paid approximately $55 
million a year for the rights. 
</P>
<P>
The new contract averages out to $112.5 million a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
