NATION; 
</P>
<P>
SPACE SHUTTLE TO RETURN SUNDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SPACE CENTER, Houston 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NASA said today that the space shuttle Atlantis will return to Earth on Sunday, 
an announcement that may indicate that the five-member military crew has 
already deployed a $500-million spy satellite. 
</P>
<P>
In a three-sentence statement that is the first break in a Pentagon-imposed 
news blackout on the military mission, NASA said the "expected landing day" for 
Atlantis is Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
No landing times were provided. 
</P>
<P>
The mission is expected to last 4 1/2 days, ending with a landing at Edwards 
Air Force Base in California. 
</P>
<P>
"The (Atlantis) crew is doing well, and orbiter Atlantis continues to perform 
satisfactorily," the terse Mission Control announcement concluded. 
</P>
<P>
The cargo carried into orbit by Atlantis reportedly is a 37,300-pound satellite 
capable of taking super-sharp photographs and listening in on electronic 
communications around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
