<P>
FLO-JO EYES OLYMPIC MARATHON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MELBOURNE, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Florence Griffith-Joyner, who retired from athletics after winning the women's 
100 and 200 meters gold medal in Seoul, has taken up marathon running and hopes 
to run in the event at the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
Griffith-Joyner also told a sports dinner Wednesday she was negotiating to play 
the part of a female James Bond in a yet to be announced film. 
</P>
<P>
The American who won three gold medals at the 1988 Olympics told a Sydney 
newspaper: "I have the dream of running the marathon because I just love 
running. I'll go out and just run and run and run along the roads. I love the 
fact of running." 
</P>
<P>
Asked at the sports dinner in Melbourne whether she seriously intended taking 
up the marathon, she said: "I'm serious about marathons and hope to run in the 
1996 Olympics." 
</P>
</TEXT>
